We had a great meal here last night (I had the Dungeness crab salad, the seared foie gras and the roasted Maine lobster; hubby had the same crab salad, the duck breast and the cheese course). Every dish we ordered was delicious, and the service was good. The ambience was nice but a bit noisier and cozier (i.e., crowded) than I would have thought it would be. It was a great meal but not one I would list as one of the best meals of my life.

Last Sunday, my boyfriend took me to Gary Danko for our anniversary. Since then, I've been obsessing over how to describe in words just how amazing the experience was. From service to cuisine to atmosphere, execution was impeccable and then some. What an incredibly pleasant and well oiled machine the house staff is. Every person had a purpose and performed his or her duty attentively and professionally without attitude or too much creepy niceness. Other restaurants should train their hospitality and service staff this well (especially Mangarosa!!!). For seven years, I've wanted to eat at Gary's but let life get in the way. Now, I want to eat at Gary's every day. I wonder if I'd have to fight other dumpster divers after hours to get leftovers ... *wink* Each of the following dishes was 5 or more stars: * Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream * Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Zucchini, English Peas and Meyer Lemon * Fried soft shelled crab with pancetta and mashed potatoes - seasonal special * Roast Maine Lobster with Morel Mushrooms, Asparagus, and Tarragon * Guinea Hen Breast with Braised-Spiced Leg in Phyllo and Grape Confit * Roasted Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Onion and Herb Spaetzle * Baked Chocolate Souffl with Two Sauces If I were a dude porno star, I would want the food at Gary Danko to be my fluffer. It does special things... *winkwinknudgenudge*

There are no words to describe how wonderful our experience was at Gary Danko! I treated my honey to a birthday dinner last night and was SOOO delighted that everything turned out PERFECT! Service is impecable. I love how they take your coat and return with it right before you leave. Our waiter was genuinely kind and ready to answer any questions about the menu. The wine sommelier seemed extremely young to me but he knew his stuff! He recommended an amazing Austrian white wine for me to have with my dishes. They have a HUGE wine list here so it was hard for me to decide on something to have with dinner. We each had 3 courses each. I had: Lobster risotto, Scallops and Quail. They all sound so plain and boring in text, but in your mouth, OMG. Flavor explosions! Birthday boy had: Seared tuna, Duck and Creme brule trio. He lucked out because his were by far the BEST choices, in addition to the scallops which were marvelous. While my risotto and quail were masterpieces in their own right, I think they over salted my dishes. You know how you think something needs more salt but by the time you think its just right, it may be too salty for others? I am giving Danko the benefit of doubt on this one. When I return, I shall try the quail again because I could still TASTE the potential in the dish and it was *close* to perfection. In the end, I will not ding Gary any stars because it really was a 5 star meal. Prepare to pay a pretty penny but it will be SO worth it. Your tummy will thank you!

I had dinner last night with a party of seven with an infant. And we had vegetarians. It's a tough party to take on and I think that the service took care of us very well. We were sat at a booth and had a chair on the end the table, making it hard for the front of house staff to reach. The staff was very accommodating and did their best to make us comfortable. The food was a mix of wonderful and ok. I got to have a bit of everything, being the only one not inhibited by any dietary restrictions. We had a great amuse bouche of a tomato and squash soup, there was a great intermezzo of berry sorbet. These were both wonderful. Desserts were sublime. I liked the apps a great deal too. It was the entrees that night that were a bit uneven. To me it seemed as though the sauce work is fantastic, the vegetables are properly cooked, but the proteins were under seasoned.

Silver bullet indeed! On the recommendation of other Yelpers, I took my ex-ex-girlfriend here last night for her birthday and our second first date. As a former waiter at a 4-Diamond establishment, I've come to both appreciate good service and be wary of spotty service at the highest levels. At Gary Denko's, however, we were treated exactly how we wished: not as royalty, but as old friends. Our captain, experts and servers were to guide us through an evening of culinary delights the palate can often only imagine. We went the 5-course route, using the Chef's tasting menu as a guide and making our own substitutions (since we obviously know better than Chef Danko which of his dishes go best together). For appetizers, my date chose the ubiquitous Ahi tuna dish (which tasted surprisingly lively with the lemon soy dressing) and I chose the seared foie gras dish. The foie gras was perhaps some of the best-cooked foie gras I've ever had, though I thought the fuji apple side overpowered it a bit. THE GODDAMNED RETARD. For our fish course, we chose the selection on the tasting menu, the horseradish salmon medallions, presumably because we are both fish philistines. Fishistines, if you will. If anyone says Phishistines, I will knock his or her teeth out. At any rate, the fish was exquisite. At one point, my date had to excuse herself momentarily, leaving me to act like I was checking text messages (like I'm important enough to even think about text messages in the middle of a fancy dinner), and I made a joke to the guy who performed the requisite folding-the-napkin-for-the-absent-seat that I had been waiting for over a minute for him to fold the napkin. I immediately realized that I had become one of the people I hated most when I worked in restaurants: the kind who make such jokes about the great service to the staff when the staff is under no pretenses or illusions and they secretly know that they're kicking ass and that the customer is an idiot. Or in my case, that I'm an idiot. But I digress. Our "main course" consisted of a (tasting menu) hen breast and risotto for her and duck breast for me. Her hen and risotto were nicely textured and my duck breast mixed quite well with the rhubarb thing on the side. Whatever. We were waiting for the CHEESE COURSE. We were presented a great array of cheeses, organized and explained to us very well by the same guy who weathered my idiotic napkin joke earlier in the night. We chose wisely and their cheeses melted our hearts. Last came the desserts (and quick accompanying coffee service-- nice job, folks): I had the trio of creme brulee (chocolate, lemon and coffee) and she had the lemon souffle cake. I'll say, it wasn't the best creme brulee I've ever had, but I prefer a slightly harder custard and a slightly softer caramelized crust, and anyway the chocolate variety was the best chocolate brulee I think I've ever had. One last surprise: a collection of birthday tarts with "Happy Birthday" written in chocolate on the plate. This is pretty much expected at a place like Gary Danko's and we were far too full to stomach the tarts, but I'm sure her roommates quite enjoyed them. And so we were sent on our merry way with a complimentary muffin, some teas, leftover tarts and high-end cheese store information. As we taxied back, I replayed the evening in my mind. Did Gary Danko have any weaknesses? Exquisite food, careful and caring service, perfect decor, exceptional cheese selection, a caring wine steward, and even reasonable prices (though we only ordered a couple glasses of wine)... is it possible that we caught Gary Danko in a moment of pure perfection? And then I thought... well, there WERE those fuji apples with the foie gras.

We always go to GD for our special occasion dinners. We have never been disappointed. Service is stellar and what is also great is that I feel just as important as the gazillionaire seated next to us. Last Friday we celebrated my GF's BDay with the 4 course selection (which we have decided is really too much food), and we both order different courses so we really have a 8 course meal. The lobster risotto is a must; my GF did share a bite or two, but that was it. Her fillet and my guinea hen breast were melt in your mouth good. We also had the ahi and avocado app, the horseradish crusted salmon, a cheese course--and yes, if you ever thought you were in the know about queso--just shut the F up and get schooled here. It all ended with the chocolate souffle as it should. We also had two half bottles of wine so we could have a lovely French Sancerre to start and creamy Merry Edwards Pinot to end with. If you haven't gone--do it. Are there better high end places? Possibly, but why deny yourself a great meal. The dining experience is in my top 3.

Another terrific meal at this amazing restaurant! Highlights from last night were: the lamb duo (perfectly cooked loin, great lamb flavor without the gaminess, along with a delicious Moroccan spiced lamb sausage) juniper crusted venison (crisp crust, tender juicy meat) lemon pepper duck breast (moist, tender and flavorful) branzini (beautifully cooked, with amazingly crispy skin) Oh, and of course, the seared foie gras. and pretty much the other courses. And the wine pairings. and the flawless, gracious service. and the ambiance. well, you get the idea...

Overpriced for what you get... Service was subpar unfortunately. The experience was a check off our list.

Rich and flavorful. No skimp portions that you might find at other dining establishments. Considering this place for a special night out? do it!

My expectations were high, but I definitely was not let down, this was easily the best meal I have ever had. The atmosphere of the restaurant was actually a lot better than I expected. I was expecting pretentious & boring and it did not have either of those qualities. There were fresh roses on every table, irises around the restaurants and cool lights, it almost looked like Las Vegas, but not in a cheesy Las Vegas kind of way. The service was impeccable & the bathrooms were so clean, it seemed like you were at a friend's house (they had real hand towels, not paper ones). The wine list was so long, that it was in a book and even had a table of contents. We each opted for the 4 course meal, which was definitely more food than we needed. The following is what we ordered: Butternut squash soup with duck confeit & bacon. - good, but could have gone without the bacon Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms & lemon soy dressing. - this was one of my favorite dishes, DELICIOUS! Savory tart of butternut squash, cipollini onions, gruyere & goat cheese mousse. - definitely up there with my favorites. Horseradish crusted salmon medallion with dilled cucumbers & mustard sauce. - this dish was good, but I wouldn't say it was one of my favorites. Herb crusted tuna with crème fraiche spaetzle, toasted pine nuts, Belgian endive & orange. - I would definitely recommend this dish. Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, celery root-garlic puree & cardamom poached pears. - another delicious dish, I would also put this one at the top of my list. Guinea hen breast with braised leg, chestnut gnocchi, Brussels sprouts, apples & pancetta. - breast was good, my favorite part of this one was the Brussels sprouts. Seared filet of beef with mashed potatoes. - good, but I have to admit that I've had a better steak. The potatoes were delicious though. Cheese cart with 15 different types of cheeses. - definitely a must have! I recommend if you go with more than one person to each get different cheeses, so you can try a variety. Bake chocolate soufflé with two sauces. - mmmmmm, I can't say not to dessert. Orange chocolate dome cake with vanilla ice cream. - delicious dessert. Banana caramel flambé prepared table side with ice cream & cake - you definitely have to order this, especially since it's prepared table side with a huge flame! It's delicious! Small tray of mini desserts - at this point we were so full, it was hard to eat this, but it was brought "complimentary"! Pumpkin cream cheese breakfast cake to go (for all the women in the restaurant) - delicious little cake to make the taste of Gary Danko last until the next day! This definitely isn't your average weekend go-to restaurant, but I highly recommend trying at least once in your lifetime. I already want to go back that food, atmosphere & service were amazing.

The wait on a Friday night during economic distress without reservations was quoted to us as 45-minutes for seating at the bar. Turned out to be more like an hour and a half. They offered a 5 course winter tasting menu for $98 dollars. I'm not a fan of cheese as a course so I opted instead for the 5 course menu of my choosing for $98. In this version, you mix and match between appetizers, fish & seafood, meat & game birds, cheese, and dessert. For items with two different prices, the higher price is meant to be a main entree (everything in the meat and game birds section was a main entree). So here's what I decided on: Course 1: Lobster Salad with Asparagus, Hearts of Palm, Mango, Lemon-Curry Vinaigrette and Pistachio Espuma - it was awesome. My only complaint was that the lobster tail itself was on the slightly chewier/tougher side. But the flavor was spot-on. Course 2: Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Fuji Apples - a must. I don't think I've ever had better prepared foie gras. They even offer the foie gras as a main entree - hello! can you say, "heart attack?" Course 3: Seared Sea Scallops with Parsnip PurÈe, Maitake Mushrooms and Sauce Maràchal - yummy. The scallop was perfectly cooked, just oh so slightly on the saltier side. Course 4: Pancetta Wrapped Frog Legs with Garlic PurÈe, Potato, Lentils and Parsley - good, but the pancetta made it slightly more salty. The sauce was just fantastic. Course 5: Rare Moroccan Spiced Squab with Chermoula and Orange-Cumin Carrots - tender and tasty. It is indeed served rare, but man was it tasty. To complete the meal, I split a couple of desserts with my CFO (it really is nice talking business in this atmosphere). Dessert 1: Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream - so incredibly good, but on the heavier side. Dessert 2: Lemon SoufflÈ Cake with CrÈme Fraiche Panna Cotta and Pomegranate Sorbet - soooo light and tart enough to cut through all of the heavier and richer foods before it. I really have to give it up to the serving staff. They apologized for the long wait and service was impeccable throughout the meal. They were warm and friendly without the pretension and stiffness you might find at some of the fancier restaurants.

We decided to go last minute and I was happy that they had full-service at the bar. Bar seating is a good option unless going to celebrate a special occassion or you have a large party. Plus, the bar server was super friendly, helpful & funny. I had 3 courses from the menu (other option is to go with the pre-set Tasting Menu). Luckily, I tasted 4 other courses, because Jaymes shared. Most memorable was the lobster salad, scallops & cheese course. Appetizer(s): Fig Salad that was really good, but not listed online. It had figs, olives, prosciutto, mixed greens sitting atop thin slices of toasted bread. It was light & tasty...I would definitely get it again. I also tasted the Lobster Salad with Avocado, Roasted Tomatoes, Shaved Fennel with Meyer Lemon-Tarragon Vinaigrette - this was perfect, especially if you like avocado, and worth going back for. Wish I had made it my main course. Main course: Selected the full-size option of Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing. The tuna was excellent, but the Lemon Soy Dressing was a bit overpowering. Less dressing would've been better. I also tasted the Seared Sea Scallops with Zucchini-Fennel Purée, Tomatoes, Red Peppers, Haricot Vert and Shimeji Mushrooms - this was really good...the scallops were perfectly done & the puree made the dish. Also, had a small bite of the Braised Veal Breast with Pistachio Crusted Sweetbreads, Potato Purée, Leeks, Capers and Chanterelle Mushrooms. Again, a great dish, but a bit on the heavier side so I wouldn't choose it as my main course. Cheese: I opted for the cheese course instead of the dessert course, but you get mini desserts anyways so it ended up as a good choice. I loved this course, because I'm a huge cheese fan and because it was fun to select the cheeses. They brought it over on a nice cart and explained all the options then run off to put your selections on a plate with bread/grapes. I had brie, cheddar, a spanish soft cheese & a hard goat cheese. All were excellent and if you love cheese then I don't think you can go wrong with any of the options. Dessert: We didnt order dessert, but they gave us a plate of min-desserts (brownie, lemon bar, coconut cookie, mini tart, etc...). I don't think you need dessert (and I'm a huge dessert fan), but this was a perfect end to the dinner. They also sent us home with some banana cheesecake. I was full before the cheese course and am glad I didn't go for the Tasting Menu. Overall, the food & service was great.

I'm going to start selling my belongings on ebay so I can eat here regularly.

A and I came here to celebrate his birthday the other night. We had originally had reservations for two weeks ago, but he unfortunately became ill and we had to cancel at the last minute. Luckily, we were able to reschedule for just two weeks later. Yay! We were able to score some rock star parking right outside the restaurant, which was doubly awesome because it was quite rainy that night. The valet guy opened the door for us and we were greeted right away by the hostess, who offered to check our coats. We decided to hold on to them though. We were seated off to the side and, as A says, if the waiter has to move your table for you to get into your seat, it must be a fancy restaurant. Anyway, I have absolutely no complaints about our very knowledgeable waiter or the impeccable service. There was always someone giving me more bread, refilling my water, taking away my empty plate, etc. As for food, we both ordered the three course tasting menu. First, everyone got a complimentary amuse bouche, which was like a round crab cake. Yes, a round crab cake. It was yummy. (1) I got the risotto with lobster and shimoji mushrooms and butternut squash. A got the dungeness crab salad with grapefruit, asian pears, mint, and yuzu remoulade. I liked my risotto. It was really thick though and they were really generous with the lobster. I have to admit, I was getting a little full just eating that alone. A liked his salad. I tried a piece of his crab and it was pretty tasty. (2) I ordered the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, celery root-garlic puree and cardamom poached pears. A had a braised rack and shoulder of lamb. I REALLY liked my duck. It was soooo good. Very tender and tons of flavor. I was getting super full by that time though, so I didn't finish all of my duck hash. I tried a piece of A's lamb, and it was really good too. He, of course, polished off the entire dish. (3) For dessert, I ordered the French macaron ice cream sandwiches with three sauces. A ordered the bittersweet chocolate mocha walnut tart with chocolate ice cream and coffee cream anglaise. I, of course, loved my ice cream sandwiches. They're macaron ice cream sandwiches! I love macarons!! They were all almond macarons, but they had pumpkin ice cream with pumpkin sauce, raspberry ice cream with raspberry sauce, and pistachio ice cream with chocolate sauce. My favorite had to be the raspberry and my least favorite the pumpkin. A said the chocolate tart was really rich though and he could've used a glass of milk. And, surprise, surprise, because we were celebrating A's birthday, they brought out this complimentary lemon mousse type dessert with a sparkly candle on top with happy birthday written on the plate in chocolate sauce. It was really pretty (and yummy)! A liked the free dessert better than the one he ordered. They also gave us the little dish of cookies afterward and the pumpkin bread to take home for breakfast the next morning. It was a really great experience and the food was incredible. So why did I give it 4 stars instead of 5? Well, the tables were a bit close together, so when the waiter was talking to the people at the next table, he stood in between our two tables and his bottom knocked over my water glass. Luckily, A and I have super quick reflexes and we both reached out and righted the glass before it tipped over completely and no one was the wiser. Later, another server was putting down plates for that same table and was standing in that same spot and totally had her bottom over our dessert and pushing against our sparkly candle. Lucky for her, A had already blown out that candle or she'd have a hot behind. So, the -1 star for that, but everything else was INCREDIBLE. Two big yums up!

I had a great experience at this restaurant. I was in town for only half a day and wanted to fit in a meal here before my flight home. I called a couple weeks ahead to make reservations and was put on a waiting list. To my surprise, they actually called 2 days prior and offered us a table. Then, we ended up running 25 minutes late due to traffic and they still accomodated us, which was amazing. The service here is absolutely impeccable. Now, on to the food. We all got 3 dishes each. My favorites were: Crusted Ahi Tuna (amazing...and with avocado - I've had a LOT of Ahi Tuna in my life, but this beats them all), scallops (melt in your mouth as they should), and the chocolate souffle (delicious and not too heavy). I also tried the lobster risotto (not bad, but not amazing), lobster/potato puree (very good), oysters with caviar (good, but I like the fun of removing them myself from the shell), horseradish crusted salmon (good, but not great), and macaroon ice cream (not my favorite thing in general, so not the restaurant's fault). I also absolutely loved the Riesling by the glass. If you like sweet Rieslings, you will love it too. Overall, the experience was unforgettable. There were so many people serving us at different points of the night, that I lost track of who was who. This isn't a bad thing since everyone was very nice and even attempted to crack jokes :) And the little surprises such as the mini desert tasting tray and the take-home desserts make this place a must on anyone's visit to SF. I would definitely come here again for another outstanding meal. There are so many things left to try on that menu. p.s. Don't forget to visit the bathroom. It's an experience in itself.

    Last Sunday, my boyfriend took me to Gary Danko for our anniversary.  Since then, I've been obsessing over how to describe in words just how amazing the experience was.  From service to cuisine to atmosphere, execution was impeccable and then some.

    There are no words to describe how wonderful our experience was at Gary Danko! I treated my honey to a birthday dinner last night and was SOOO delighted that everything turned out PERFECT!

    Service is impecable. I love how they take your coat and return with it right before you leave. Our waiter was genuinely kind and ready to answer any questions about the menu.

    The wine sommelier seemed extremely young to me but he knew his stuff! He recommended an amazing Austrian white wine for me to have with my dishes. They have a HUGE wine list here so it was hard for me to decide on something to have with dinner.

    We each had 3 courses each.

    I had: Lobster risotto, Scallops and Quail. They all sound so plain and boring in text, but in your mouth, OMG. Flavor explosions!

    Birthday boy had: Seared tuna, Duck and Creme brule trio. He lucked out because his were by far the BEST choices, in addition to the scallops which were marvelous.

    While my risotto and quail were masterpieces in their own right, I think they over salted my dishes. You know how you think something needs more salt but by the time you think its just right, it may be too salty for others? I am giving Danko the benefit of doubt on this one. When I return, I shall try the quail again because I could still TASTE the potential in the dish and it was *close* to perfection.

    In the end, I will not ding Gary any stars because it really was a 5 star meal. Prepare to pay a pretty penny but it will be SO worth it. Your tummy will thank you!

    4/14/2006

    Silver bullet indeed!

    On the recommendation of other Yelpers, I took my ex-ex-girlfriend here last night for her birthday and our second first date.  As a former waiter at a 4-Diamond establishment, I've come to both appreciate good service and be wary of spotty service at the highest levels.  At Gary Denko's, however, we were treated exactly how we wished: not as royalty, but as old friends.  Our captain, experts and servers were to guide us through an evening of culinary delights the palate can often only imagine.

    We went the 5-course route, using the Chef's tasting menu as a guide and making our own substitutions (since we obviously know better than Chef Danko which of his dishes go best together).  For appetizers, my date chose the ubiquitous Ahi tuna dish (which tasted surprisingly lively with the lemon soy dressing) and I chose the seared foie gras dish.  The foie gras was perhaps some of the best-cooked foie gras I've ever had, though I thought the fuji apple side overpowered it a bit.  THE GODDAMNED RETARD.

    For our fish course, we chose the selection on the tasting menu, the horseradish salmon medallions, presumably because we are both fish philistines.  Fishistines, if you will.  If anyone says Phishistines, I will knock his or her teeth out.  At any rate, the fish was exquisite.

    At one point, my date had to excuse herself momentarily, leaving me to act like I was checking text messages (like I'm important enough to even think about text messages in the middle of a fancy dinner), and I made a joke to the guy who performed the requisite folding-the-napkin-for-the-absent-seat that I had been waiting for over a minute for him to fold the napkin.  I immediately realized that I had become one of the people I hated most when I worked in restaurants: the kind who make such jokes about the great service to the staff when the staff is under no pretenses or illusions and they secretly know that they're kicking ass and that the customer is an idiot.  Or in my case, that I'm an idiot.  But I digress.

    Our "main course" consisted of a (tasting menu) hen breast and risotto for her and duck breast for me.  Her hen and risotto were nicely textured and my duck breast mixed quite well with the rhubarb thing on the side.  Whatever.  We were waiting for the CHEESE COURSE.  We were presented a great array of cheeses, organized and explained to us very well by the same guy who weathered my idiotic napkin joke earlier in the night.  We chose wisely and their cheeses melted our hearts.

    Last came the desserts (and quick accompanying coffee service-- nice job, folks): I had the trio of creme brulee (chocolate, lemon and coffee) and she had the lemon souffle cake.  I'll say, it wasn't the best creme brulee I've ever had, but I prefer a slightly harder custard and a slightly softer caramelized crust, and anyway the chocolate variety was the best chocolate brulee I think I've ever had.  One last surprise: a collection of birthday tarts with "Happy Birthday" written in chocolate on the plate.  This is pretty much expected at a place like Gary Danko's and we were far too full to stomach the tarts, but I'm sure her roommates quite enjoyed them.

    And so we were sent on our merry way with a complimentary muffin, some teas, leftover tarts and high-end cheese store information.  As we taxied back, I replayed the evening in my mind.  Did Gary Danko have any weaknesses?  Exquisite food, careful and caring service, perfect decor, exceptional cheese selection, a caring wine steward, and even reasonable prices (though we only ordered a couple glasses of wine)... is it possible that we caught Gary Danko in a moment of pure perfection?  And then I thought... well, there WERE those fuji apples with the foie gras.

    2/7/2009

    My expectations were high, but I definitely was not let down, this was easily the best meal I have ever had. The atmosphere of the restaurant was actually a lot better than I expected. I was expecting pretentious & boring and it did not have either of those qualities. There were fresh roses on every table, irises around the restaurants and cool lights, it almost looked like Las Vegas, but not in a cheesy Las Vegas kind of way. The service was impeccable & the bathrooms were so clean, it seemed like you were at a friend's house (they had real hand towels, not paper ones). The wine list was so long, that it was in a book and even had a table of contents. We each opted for the 4 course meal, which was definitely more food than we needed. The following is what we ordered:

    Butternut squash soup with duck confeit & bacon. - good, but could have gone without the bacon

    Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms & lemon soy dressing. - this was one of my favorite dishes, DELICIOUS!

    Savory tart of butternut squash, cipollini onions, gruyere & goat cheese mousse. - definitely up there with my favorites.

    Horseradish crusted salmon medallion with dilled cucumbers & mustard sauce. - this dish was good, but I wouldn't say it was one of my favorites.

    Herb crusted tuna with crème fraiche spaetzle, toasted pine nuts, Belgian endive & orange. - I would definitely recommend this dish.

    Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, celery root-garlic puree & cardamom poached pears. - another delicious dish, I would also put this one at the top of my list.

    Guinea hen breast with braised leg, chestnut gnocchi, Brussels sprouts, apples & pancetta. - breast was good, my favorite part of this one was the Brussels sprouts.

    Seared filet of beef with mashed potatoes. - good, but I have to admit that I've had a better steak. The potatoes were delicious though.

    Cheese cart with 15 different types of cheeses. - definitely a must have! I recommend if you go with more than one person to each get different cheeses, so you can try a variety.

    Bake chocolate soufflé with two sauces. - mmmmmm, I can't say not to dessert.

    Orange chocolate dome cake with vanilla ice cream. - delicious dessert.

    Banana caramel flambé prepared table side with ice cream & cake - you definitely have to order this, especially since it's prepared table side with a huge flame! It's delicious!

    Small tray of mini desserts - at this point we were so full, it was hard to eat this, but it was brought "complimentary"!

    Pumpkin cream cheese breakfast cake to go (for all the women in the restaurant) - delicious little cake to make the taste of Gary Danko last until the next day!

    This definitely isn't your average weekend go-to restaurant, but I highly recommend trying at least once in your lifetime. I already want to go back that food, atmosphere & service were amazing.

    3/14/2009

    The wait on a Friday night during economic distress without reservations was quoted to us as 45-minutes for seating at the bar.  Turned out to be more like an hour and a half.

    They offered a 5 course winter tasting menu for $98 dollars.  I'm not a fan of cheese as a course so I opted instead for the 5 course menu of my choosing for $98.  In this version, you mix and match between appetizers, fish & seafood, meat & game birds, cheese, and dessert.  For items with two different prices, the higher price is meant to be a main entree (everything in the meat and game birds section was a main entree).

    So here's what I decided on:

    Course 1:  Lobster Salad with Asparagus, Hearts of Palm, Mango, Lemon-Curry Vinaigrette and Pistachio Espuma - it was awesome.  My only complaint was that the lobster tail itself was on the slightly chewier/tougher side.  But the flavor was spot-on.

    Course 2:  Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Fuji Apples - a must.  I don't think I've ever had better prepared foie gras.  They even offer the foie gras as a main entree - hello!  can you say, "heart attack?"

    Course 3:  Seared Sea Scallops with Parsnip PurÈe, Maitake Mushrooms and Sauce Maràchal - yummy.  The scallop was perfectly cooked, just oh so slightly on the saltier side.

    Course 4:  Pancetta Wrapped Frog Legs with Garlic PurÈe, Potato, Lentils and Parsley - good, but the pancetta made it slightly more salty.  The sauce was just fantastic.

    Course 5:  Rare Moroccan Spiced Squab with Chermoula and Orange-Cumin Carrots - tender and tasty.  It is indeed served rare, but man was it tasty.

    To complete the meal, I split a couple of desserts with my CFO (it really is nice talking business in this atmosphere).  

    Dessert 1:  Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream - so incredibly good, but on the heavier side.

    Dessert 2:  Lemon SoufflÈ Cake with CrÈme Fraiche Panna Cotta and Pomegranate Sorbet - soooo light and tart enough to cut through all of the heavier and richer foods before it.

    I really have to give it up to the serving staff.  They apologized for the long wait and service was impeccable throughout the meal.  They were warm and friendly without the pretension and stiffness you might find at some of the fancier restaurants.

    8/31/2010

    We decided to go last minute and I was happy that they had full-service at the bar.  Bar seating is a good option unless going to celebrate a special occassion or you have a large party.  Plus, the bar server was super friendly, helpful & funny.

    I had 3 courses from the menu (other option is to go with the pre-set Tasting Menu).  Luckily, I tasted 4 other courses, because Jaymes shared.  Most memorable was the lobster salad, scallops & cheese course.

    Appetizer(s):  Fig Salad that was really good, but not listed online.  It had figs, olives, prosciutto, mixed greens sitting atop thin slices of toasted bread.  It was light & tasty...I would definitely get it again.  I also tasted the Lobster Salad with Avocado, Roasted Tomatoes, Shaved Fennel with Meyer Lemon-Tarragon Vinaigrette - this was perfect, especially if you like avocado, and worth going back for.  Wish I had made it my main course.

    Main course:  Selected the full-size option of Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing.  The tuna was excellent, but the Lemon Soy Dressing was a bit overpowering.  Less dressing would've been better.  I also tasted the Seared Sea Scallops with Zucchini-Fennel Purée, Tomatoes, Red Peppers, Haricot Vert and Shimeji Mushrooms - this was really good...the scallops were perfectly done & the puree made the dish.  Also, had a small bite of the Braised Veal Breast with Pistachio Crusted Sweetbreads, Potato Purée, Leeks, Capers and Chanterelle Mushrooms.  Again, a great dish, but a bit on the heavier side so I wouldn't choose it as my main course.

    Cheese:  I opted for the cheese course instead of the dessert course, but you get mini desserts anyways so it ended up as a good choice.  I loved this course, because I'm a huge cheese fan and because it was fun to select the cheeses.  They brought it over on a nice cart and explained all the options then run off to put your selections on a plate with bread/grapes.  I had brie, cheddar, a spanish soft cheese & a hard goat cheese.  All were excellent and if you love cheese then I don't think you can go wrong with any of the options.

    Dessert:  We didnt order dessert, but they gave us a plate of min-desserts (brownie, lemon bar, coconut cookie, mini tart, etc...).  I don't think you need dessert (and I'm a huge dessert fan), but this was a perfect end to the dinner.  They also sent us home with some banana cheesecake.

    I was full before the cheese course and am glad I didn't go for the Tasting Menu.  Overall, the food & service was great.

    1/24/2010

    A and I came here to celebrate his birthday the other night.  We had originally had reservations for two weeks ago, but he unfortunately became ill and we had to cancel at the last minute.  Luckily, we were able to reschedule for just two weeks later.  Yay!

    We were able to score some rock star parking right outside the restaurant, which was doubly awesome because it was quite rainy that night.  The valet guy opened the door for us and we were greeted right away by the hostess, who offered to check our coats.  We decided to hold on to them though.  We were seated off to the side and, as A says, if the waiter has to move your table for you to get into your seat, it must be a fancy restaurant.  Anyway, I have absolutely no complaints about our very knowledgeable waiter or the impeccable service.  There was always someone giving me more bread, refilling my water, taking away my empty plate, etc.

    As for food, we both ordered the three course tasting menu.  First, everyone got a complimentary amuse bouche, which was like a round crab cake.  Yes, a round crab cake.  It was yummy.
    (1) I got the risotto with lobster and shimoji mushrooms and butternut squash.  A got the dungeness crab salad with grapefruit, asian pears, mint, and yuzu remoulade.  

    I liked my risotto.  It was really thick though and they were really generous with the lobster.  I have to admit, I was getting a little full just eating that alone.  A liked his salad.  I tried a piece of his crab and it was pretty tasty.

    (2) I ordered the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, celery root-garlic puree and cardamom poached pears.  A had a braised rack and shoulder of lamb.

    I REALLY liked my duck.  It was soooo good.  Very tender and tons of flavor.  I was getting super full by that time though, so I didn't finish all of my duck hash.  I tried a piece of A's lamb, and it was really good too.  He, of course, polished off the entire dish.

    (3) For dessert, I ordered the French macaron ice cream sandwiches with three sauces.  A ordered the bittersweet chocolate mocha walnut tart with chocolate ice cream and coffee cream anglaise.

    I, of course, loved my ice cream sandwiches.  They're macaron ice cream sandwiches!  I love macarons!!  They were all almond macarons, but they had pumpkin ice cream with pumpkin sauce, raspberry ice cream with raspberry sauce, and pistachio ice cream with chocolate sauce.  My favorite had to be the raspberry and my least favorite the pumpkin.  A said the chocolate tart was really rich though and he could've used a glass of milk.

    And, surprise, surprise, because we were celebrating A's birthday, they brought out this complimentary lemon mousse type dessert with a sparkly candle on top with happy birthday written on the plate in chocolate sauce.  It was really pretty (and yummy)!  A liked the free dessert better than the one he ordered.  

    They also gave us the little dish of cookies afterward and the pumpkin bread to take home for breakfast the next morning.

    It was a really great experience and the food was incredible.  So why did I give it 4 stars instead of 5?  Well, the tables were a bit close together, so when the waiter was talking to the people at the next table, he stood in between our two tables and his bottom knocked over my water glass.  Luckily, A and I have super quick reflexes and we both reached out and righted the glass before it tipped over completely and no one was the wiser.  Later, another server was putting down plates for that same table and was standing in that same spot and totally had her bottom over our dessert and pushing against our sparkly candle.  Lucky for her, A had already blown out that candle or she'd have a hot behind.

    So, the -1 star for that, but everything else was INCREDIBLE.  Two big yums up!
